# Line-ending policy for CUupdateTool.
#
# Problem this solves: source files were authored LF, but Windows clones with
# core.autocrlf=true check them out as CRLF, so `git status` permanently shows
# them "modified" (LF<->CRLF only) and a `git pull` won't fast-forward over
# them. That caused a real incident (a build silently ran the OLD cu.spec
# because the new one couldn't be pulled in over the phantom-modified files).
#
# Policy:
#   - SOURCE files (code, docs, build): normalised. Stored as LF in the repo,
#     checked out using the platform's native ending. No more phantom diffs.
#   - C/AL OBJECT TEXT (.txt) + the test FIXTURES and SAMPLES: frozen as-is.
#     These are byte-exact known-answer artifacts; the execution tests compare
#     them after their OWN normalisation, and some are deliberately CRLF
#     (TortoiseMerge artifacts) while others are LF. Git must NEVER rewrite
#     their line endings or the fixtures would change bytes and break the
#     byte-exact tests. `-text` = treat as binary for EOL purposes (no convert).

# --- source: normalise to LF in repo, native on checkout ---
*.py    text eol=lf
*.md    text eol=lf
*.spec  text eol=lf
*.js    text eol=lf
*.json  text eol=lf
.gitignore   text eol=lf
.gitattributes text eol=lf

# --- C/AL object text and known-answer artifacts: freeze bytes, never convert ---
*.txt   -text
tests/fixtures/**  -text
samples/**         -text

# --- binary artifacts (already effectively binary; be explicit) ---
*.docx  binary
*.png   binary
*.exe   binary
*.zip   binary
*.patch -text
